around a point $(h, k)$ is:\n\\[ \\begin{pmatrix} \\cos 90^\\circ & -\\sin 90^\\circ \\\\ \\sin 90^\\circ & \\cos 90^\\circ \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & -1 \\\\ 1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix} \\]\n\nThe coordinates of a point $(x, y)$ after a $90^\\circ$ counterclockwise rotation around $(h, k)$ can be found using the transformation:\n\\[ \\begin{pmatrix} x' \\\\ y' \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} -1 & -1 + h \\\\ 1 & 1 - k \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} x - h \\\\ y - k \\end{pmatrix} \\]\n\nFor point $Q(2, 7)$ and point $M(2, 5)$, the transformation is:\n\\[ \\begin{pmatrix} x' \\\\ y' \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & -1 \\\\ 1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} 2 - 2 \\\\ 7 - 5 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & -1 \\\\ 1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\ 2 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\ 2 \\end{pmatrix} \\]\n\nSo after the rotation, the new coordinates of $Q$ are $(0, 2)$. However, we need to shift these coordinates back since the rotation was around $M(2, 5)$, not the origin. The original coordinates of $Q$ were $(2, 7)$ and it was rotated around $(2, 5)$, so we need to shift the points $(2, 7)$ and $(0, 2)$ back by $(2, 5)$ to get the new positions relative to the original coordinates.\n\nThus, the new coordinates of $Q$ after the rotation are:\n\\[ (0 + 2, 2 + 5) = (2, 7) + (2, -2) = (2, 5) \\]\n\n**Step 2: Reflect the point around the line $x = 1$.**\n\nTo reflect a point $(x, y)$ across the line $x = 1$, we use the formula:\n\\[ (x', y') = (2 \\cdot 1 - x, y) = (2 - x, y) \\]\n\nSo reflecting the point $(2, 5)$ across the line $x = 1$ gives us:\n\\[ (2 - 2, 5) = (0, 5) \\]\n\nThus, the final coordinates of the image of point $Q$ are $(0, 5)$.\n\nThe complete code in Python using sympy to verify this would be:\n\n```python\nimport sympy as sp\n\n# Initial coordinates of Q\nQ = sp.Point(2, 7)\n\n# Rotate 270 degrees clockwise around M(2, 5)\nM = sp.Point(2, 5)\nQ_rotated = Q.rotate(sp.Rot(90, M))\n\n# Reflect the point around the